             </li><li class="sense" sensenum="3" htag="li" hclass="sense" id="argue_sng_3"><span class="sensetop" htag="span" hclass="sensetop"><span class="grammar" hclass="grammar" htag="span">[transitive]</span></span> <span class="cf" hclass="cf" htag="span">argue something</span> <span class="labels" htag="span" hclass="labels">(formal)</span> <span class="def" hclass="def" htag="span">to show clearly that something exists or is true</span><ul class="examples" hclass="examples" htag="ul"><li class="" htag="li"><span class="x">These latest developments argue a change in government policy.</span></li></ul>      </li><div class="collapse" hclass="collapse" htag="div"><span class="unbox" unbox="wordorigin" id="argue_unbox_9"><span class="box_title">Word Origin</span><span class="body"><span class="p">Middle English: from Old French <span class="ei">arguer</span>, from Latin <span class="ei">argutari</span> ‘prattle’, frequentative of <span class="ei">arguere</span> ‘make clear, prove, accuse’.</span></span></span></div></ol><div class="idioms" hclass="idioms" id="argue_idmgs_1" htag="div"><span class="idioms_heading">Idioms</span> <span class="idm-g" sk="arguetoss" id="argue_idmg_1"><div class="top-container"><div class="top-g" id="argue_topg_2"><div class="webtop"><span class="idm" id="argue_idm_1" cefr="c2">argue the toss</span> </div></div></div><ol class="sense_single" htag="ol"><li class="sense" hclass="sense" fkcefr="c2" id="argue_sng_4" htag="li"><span class="sensetop" htag="span" hclass="sensetop"><span class="labels" htag="span" hclass="labels">(British English, informal)</span></span> <span class="def" htag="span" hclass="def">to continue to disagree about a decision, especially when it is too late to change it or it is not very important</span><span class="topic-g"><span class="prefix">Topics </span><a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/topic/opinion-and-argument?level=c2" title="Topic opinion-and-argument"><span class="topic" h